Lossy is much like Lossy file compression, which discards some data, resulting in smaller files but potentially lower quality. Great! Dorothy and Lossy land with an almighty crash, in a far away land. Just as she steadies herself, a friendly witch named GLINDA arrives and happily tells Dorothy that she has landed in "Migration-Land" in the mythical "Land of Oz-bolescence". The Migration-Landkins are celebrating because the same storm that carried Dorothy, also swept away the Wicked Witch of the East. Although, her sister, the Wicked Witch of the West, will seek revenge on Dorothy! Glinda gives Dorothy the witch's magical "DPC Handbook", which will help her navigate the evil paths of data loss and keep her safe in her journey to visit the Wizard who can take her home! It is very useful for anyone interested in Digital Preservation. Glinda tells Dorothy to follow the (Archivematica)-orange brick road, which will lead to a wizard who can get her home. But be careful, as the Wicked Witch will try to stop her! Dorothy and Lossy proceed along the road where they come accross a scarecrow! He is very upset, as he has lots of digital files but does not know much about them. The scarecrow needs a tool or technology of some kind that can help analyse all of his files, apply checksums, and identify their file formats. But he does not have the brain power to identify what he needs. ||||= Using her trusty DPC Handbook, Dorothy thinks she can help him. [DROID (Digital Record Object Identification) is a free software tool developed by The National Archives, which can help the Scarecrow to profile his file formats and understand more about them. The Scarecrow needs to use DROID, but the only person in the land who knows how to download it is the Wizard, so he happily joins Dorothy on her travels. Their next encounter is with a Lion, who is sad and crying. The Lion lacks the courage to convince his other Lion friends that digital preservation is important! He needs something to help him with advocacy! Dorothy reads her DPC handbook again and notices an advocacy section with details about how to engage with stakeholders, see: https://www.dpconline.org/handbook/institutional-strategies/advocacy] ||||= The Lion is curious about this and asks what the first step would be. The Evil Witch vows to put a spell on them all, but she has a problem. The spell she wishes to cast is stored within a Floppy Disc. And she cannot seem to be able to get access to it. Before engaging with stakeholders, it is important for the Lion to start with a clear understanding of his aims. This will help focus his advocacy efforts and can be tailored to his different audiences. The Lion now has the courage he needs to help convince his lion friends that they should undertake digital preservation. He wants to ask the Wizard for any tips he may have and so joins the merry gang. As they travel further down the orange path they happen across a very despondent Tin-Man. He has far too much digital content to preserve but does not have the heart to know what he should prioritise. It all seems so important! ||||= Dorothy once again reads her handbook, and finds something that may be of use to the Tin-Man, see:
